      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The evidence is not a simple \"people don't want to work\" narrative; rather, the structure of the benefits is the primary driver. Studies show that benefit cliffs—where earning slightly more income causes a drastic loss of aid—create a powerful disincentive to seek higher-paying jobs. These programs are often designed with complexity that unintentionally penalizes work effort, which is a major policy design flaw.",
